{"title_page": "James Richard Dacres (Royal Navy officer, born 1788)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}{{Infobox military person\n|name=James Richard Dacres\n|birth_date=22 August 1788\n|death_date={{death date and age|df=yes|1853|12|4|1788|6|22}}\n|image=\n|caption=\n|birth_place = [[Lowestoft]]\n|death_place = Catisfield Lodge, near [[Fareham]], [[Hampshire]]\n|nickname=\n|residence =  [[United Kingdom]]\n|nationality =  [[United Kingdom|British]]\n|allegiance={{Flagcountry|UKGBI}}\n|serviceyears= 1796 &ndash; 1853\n|rank=[[Admiral (United Kingdom)|Vice-Admiral]]\n|branch= {{Navy|UK}}\n|commands={{HMS|Elk|1804|6}}<br>[[French corvette Bacchante (1795)|HMS ''Bacchante'']]<br>{{HMS|Guerriere|1806|6}}<br>{{HMS|Tiber|1813|6}}<br>{{HMS|Edinburgh|1811|6}}<br>[[Cape of Good Hope Station]]\n|unit=\n|battles=[[USS Constitution vs HMS Guerriere|USS ''Constitution'' vs HMS ''Guerriere'']]\n|awards=\n|relations=[[James Richard Dacres (1749\u20131810)|James Richard Dacres]] (father)<br>[[Barrington Dacres]] (brother)<br>[[Richard Dacres (Royal Navy officer)|Richard Dacres]] (uncle)<br>[[Sydney Dacres]] (cousin)\n}}\n\n'''James Richard Dacres''' (22 August 1788 &ndash; 4 December 1853) was an officer of the [[Royal Navy]] who saw service during the [[French Revolutionary War|French Revolutionary]] and [[Napoleonic Wars]], and the [[War of 1812]].  A member of a substantial naval dynasty, he eventually rose to the rank of [[Vice admiral (Royal Navy)|vice admiral]], but is chiefly remembered for his engagement with the American [[frigate]] {{USS|Constitution}} which saw the loss of his ship, {{HMS|Guerriere|1806|6}}.\n\n==Family and early life==\nDacres was born in [[Lowestoft]] on 22 August 1788, the son of Captain, later Vice-Admiral, [[James Richard Dacres (1749\u20131810)|James Richard Dacres]] and his wife Eleanor Blandford Pearce.<ref name=\"Whos Who108\">{{cite book |last=Tracy  |title=Who's who in Nelson's Navy |page=108}}</ref><ref name=\"GM201\">{{cite journal |title=Obituary: Vice-Admiral Dacres |journal=[[The Gentleman's Magazine]] |volume=XLI |issue=I |page=201 |url=http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=chi.79255342;view=1up;seq=213 |year=1854 |accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref> The Dacres would eventually become a substantial naval dynasty, James's elder brother [[Barrington Dacres]] embarked on a naval career and rose to be [[post-captain]], while their uncle, [[Richard Dacres (Royal Navy officer)|Richard Dacres]] became a vice-admiral. His cousin, Richard's son [[Sydney Dacres]] would eventually be an admiral, and [[First Sea Lord]].<ref name=\"Whos Who108\"/> James Richard Dacres entered the navy in 1796 at the age of eight, serving aboard his father's old ship, the 64-gun {{HMS|Sceptre|1781|6}}, as a first class volunteer.<ref name=\"GM201\"/> He moved aboard the 98-gun {{HMS|Barfleur|1768|6}} in 1797 and was present during the expedition to [[Ferrol, Spain|Ferrol]] in August 1800 as a lieutenant aboard the 74-gun [[French ship America (1788)|HMS ''Impetueux'']].<ref name=\"GM201\"/>\n\nHe was next reported aboard the 38-gun frigate {{HMS|Boadicea|1797|6}}, serving in the [[English Channel]] under Captain [[John Maitland (Royal Navy officer)|John Maitland]].<ref name=\"GM202\"/> On 24 July 1803 the French 74-gun [[third-rate]] [[HMS Implacable (1805)|''Duguay-Trouin'']] and the 38-gun frigate [[HMS Guerriere (1806)|''Guerri\u00e8re'']] were sighted sailing off [[Ferrol, Spain]].<ref name=\"Tracy238\">{{cite book |last=Tracy |title=Who's who in Nelson's Navy |page=238}}</ref><ref name=\"GM654\">{{cite book|title=Gentleman's Magazine|year=1837 |page=654}}</ref> Maitland decided to test whether the French ships were armed [[en fl\u00fbte]] and were being used as [[troopship]]s, and closing to within range, opened fire. The French returned fire, revealing they were fully armed and manned, and Maitland broke off. The French pursued, but were unable to catch him.<ref name=\"Tracy238\"/><ref name=\"GM654\"/> This marked Dacres's first encounter with the ''Guerri\u00e8re'', a ship he was later to command under the British flag.\n\nDacres then moved to the [[West Indies]], where his father was commander in chief of the [[Jamaica Station (Royal Navy)|Jamaica Station]]. He served for some time as [[flag lieutenant]] aboard {{HMS|Theseus|1786|6}} and [[French ship Hercule (1798)|HMS ''Hercule'']] before being appointed to his first command, that of the 18-gun [[Cruizer class brig-sloop|''Cruizer'' class]] [[brig-sloop]] {{HMS|Elk|1804|6}}.<ref name=\"GM202\">{{cite journal |title=Obituary: Vice-Admiral Dacres |journal=[[The Gentleman's Magazine]] |volume=XLI |issue=I |page=202 |url=http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=chi.79255342;view=1up;seq=214 |year=1854 |accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"AR275\">{{cite book|last=Dodsley|title=Annual Register|page=275}}</ref>\n\n==Command==\nDacres remained in command aboard the ''Elk'' until being transferred to the 24-gun {{HMS|Bacchante|1803|6}} on 14 January 1806.<ref name=\"GM202\"/><ref name=\"AR275\"/> While in command of her he captured the 3-gun French [[schooner]] ''Dauphin'', crewed with 71 men, off [[St. Domingo]] on 14 February 1807.<ref name=\"GM202\"/><ref name=\"AR275\"/> He then fell in with Captain [[William Furlong Wise]] of [[Ann and Amelia (1781 ship)|''Mediator'']] and together they navigated the waters around [[Saman\u00e1 (town)|Samana]] and planned an attack on the fort there, which was a notorious haven for [[privateer]]s. The two ships mounted a four-hour-long carronade, before [[Raid on Saman\u00e1|storming the defenders]]. They captured the fort, suffering two killed and 16 wounded in the process.<ref name=\"GM202\"/><ref name=\"AR275\"/> Dacres returned to England after this, but on his arrival in December 1807 no command could be found for him and he went on half-pay.<ref name=\"GM202\"/>\n\n===North America and the ''Guerriere''===\nHe returned to active service again on 18 March 1811, when he was appointed to command the former French frigate {{HMS|Guerriere|1806|6}}, which had been captured by [[HMS Amfitrite (1804)|HMS ''Blanche'']] on 19 July 1806.<ref name=\"Colledge150\">{{cite book|last=Colledge|title=Ships of the Royal Navy|page=150}}</ref>  Dacres sailed to the North American station, and shortly after the outbreak of the [[War of 1812]] was despatched by Vice-Admiral [[Herbert Sawyer]] as part of a squadron under Captain [[Philip Broke]] to intercept an American  squadron under Commodore [[John Rodgers (naval officer, War of 1812)|John Rodgers]]. Broke's squadron consisted of the 64-gun [[ship of the line]] {{HMS|Africa|1781|6}} and the frigates ''[[HMS Shannon (1806)|Shannon]]'', ''[[HMS Aeolus (1801)|Aeolus]]'', {{HMS|Belvidera|1809|2}} and ''Guerriere''.<ref name=\"Borneman82\">{{cite book|last=Borneman|title=1812: The War That Forged a Nation|page=82}}</ref>\n\nDacres briefly became separated from Broke's squadron, and while returning to them on 17 August came across the {{USS|Constitution}}, under Captain [[Isaac Hull]]. He mistook the other nearby ships, which was Broke's squadron, for the American squadron under Rodgers, and so missed an opportunity to close on the ''Constitution''.<ref name=\"Forester38\">{{cite book|last=Forester|title=The Age of Fighting Sail|page=38}}</ref> A chase ensued between the British and American ships, but the ''Constitution'' was finally able to escape Broke's squadron. Dacres remained with Broke, joining him in August in escorting an inbound convoy to [[City of Halifax|Halifax]], after which Dacres and the ''Guerriere'' were detached to sail to Halifax and undergo a refit.<ref name=\"Forester45\">{{cite book|last=Forester|title=The Age of Fighting Sail|page=45}}</ref>\n\n===Battling the ''Constitution''===\n{{Main|USS Constitution vs HMS Guerriere}}\n[[File:USS Constitution vs Guerriere.jpg|thumb|right|Painting of combat between USS ''Constitution'' and HMS ''Guerriere'' by Michel Felice Corne]]\nOn the afternoon of 19 August the ''Guerriere'' made contact with the ''Constitution''. Dacres prepared to fight and the two ships closed and exchanged broadsides for some time. The range eventually decreased and after a brief close exchange the ''Guerriere''{{'}}s mizzenmast was shot away, allowing the ''Constitution'' to rake her several times, causing considerable damage, before the two ships became entangled. Shortly after this ''Guerriere'' lost both her main and foremasts, leaving her largely un-manoeuvrable.<ref name=\"Forester52\">{{cite book|last=Forester|title=The Age of Fighting Sail|page=52}}</ref> During the engagement Dacres had been wounded by a musket-ball in the back while on the starboard forecastle, but had refused to leave the deck.<ref name=\"GM202\"/> ''Constitution'' then drew away to repair some damage, while Dacres attempted to set a jury rig. The attempt failed, and on ''Constitution''{{'}}s returning, Dacres fired a shot in the opposite direction to the ''Constitution''.<ref name=\"Borneman86\">{{cite book|last=Borneman|title=1812: The War That Forged a Nation|page=86}}</ref> Sensing that this was an attempt to signal surrender, Hull ordered a boat to take a lieutenant over to the British ship. When the lieutenant walked onto the ''Guerriere'' and asked if ''Guerriere'' was prepared to surrender, Captain Dacres responded \"Well, Sir, I don't know. Our mizzen mast is gone, our fore and main masts are gone-I think on the whole you might say we have struck our flag.\"<ref name=\"Borneman87\">{{cite book|last=Borneman|title=1812: The War That Forged a Nation|page=87}}</ref>\n\nDacres was brought aboard the ''Constitution'' where he presented his sword to Hull. Hull refused to accept it, saying he could not accept the sword from a man who had fought so gallantly.<ref name=\"Borneman87\"/>   Hull did, however, take possession of Dacres' hat to settle a wager the two had made earlier over who's ship was better.  Hull also ordered that Dacres' mother's Bible be returned to him.<ref name=\"Borneman87\"/> The ''Guerriere'' was assessed but found to be unsalvageable, and was blown up.<ref name=\"Colledge150\"/>\n\n===Aftermath===\n{{Wikisource|Letter from Captain James R. Dacres, RN, to Vice Admiral Herbert Sawyer, RN}}\nDacres briefly became a [[prisoner of war]], but was [[prisoner exchange|exchanged]] and returned to Halifax, where he was tried by [[court martial]] for the loss of his ship, which was standard procedure in the Royal Navy for the loss of a ship at the time.<ref name=\"GM202\"/><ref name=\"AR275\"/> He put forward as his defence the facts that the ''Guerriere'' was originally French-built and therefore not as sturdy as British-built ships, and that the ''Guerriere'' was badly decayed and on her way to refit in Halifax at the time, and the fall of the mizzen mast which crippled the ''Guerriere'' early in the fight had been due as much to rot as battle damage.<ref name=\"Forester50-1\">{{cite book|last=Forester|title=The Age of Fighting Sail|pages=50\u20131}}</ref> There was no suggestion that Dacres and his men had not done their utmost, or that Dacres had been unwise to engage the ''Constitution''. He was therefore honourably acquitted of all blame for the loss.<ref name=\"GM202\"/><ref name=\"AR275\"/><ref name=\"Forester56-7\">{{cite book|last=Forester|title=The Age of Fighting Sail|pages=56\u20137}}</ref> He was awarded a gratuity from the Lloyd's Patriotic Fund in consideration of his wound.<ref name=\"GM202\"/><ref name=\"AR275\"/>\n\n==Promotion==\nDacres continued to serve in the navy after his acquittal, and was appointed to the new 38-gun frigate {{HMS|Tiber|1813|6}} on 23 July 1814.<ref name=\"GM202\"/> He commanded her on the [[Cork (city)|Cork]], [[Newfoundland and Labrador|Newfoundland]] and Channel stations until 18 September 1818. On 8 March 1815 he captured the ''Leo'', a 3-gun American privateer under Captain George Coggeshell.<ref name=\"GM202\"/> He was appointed to command the 74-gun [[third rate]] {{HMS|Edinburgh|1811|6}} on 28 October 1833 until 1837.<ref name=\"GM202\"/> He became a rear-admiral on 28 June 1838, and commander-in-chief of the [[Cape of Good Hope Station]] on 9 August 1845, which was his last active employment.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hiscocks|first1=Richard|title=Cape Commander-in-Chief 1795-1852|url=http://morethannelson.com/commander-chief-cape/|website=morethannelson.com|publisher=morethannelson.com|accessdate=19 November 2016}}</ref> A temporary [[fort]] built in 1846 at the mouth of the [[Great Fish River|Fish River]] in the [[Eastern Cape|Eastern Cape Province]] during the [[Xhosa Wars#Seventh war|Seventh Xhosa War]] was named Fort Dacres in his honour. The construction was carried out by [[sailor]]s of the British [[man-of-war]] [[HMS President (1829)|HMS ''President'']].<ref>\n{{cite encyclopedia|title=Fort Dacres|encyclopedia=Standard Encyclopaedia of Southern Africa|volume=4|pages=646|publisher=Nasionale Opvoedkundige Uitgewery Ltd, Cape Town|date=1971|isbn = 0625003209}}</ref>\n\nHe was promoted to vice-admiral on 20 March 1848.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=20840|page=1182|date=24 March 1848}}</ref>\n\n==Family and later life==\nDacres married Arabella-Boyd, sister of [[Sir Adolphus Dalrymple, 2nd Baronet|Sir Adolphus Dalrymple]], on 25 April 1810.<ref name=\"GM202\"/> She died on 11 April 1828, but the marriage produced two sons and five daughters.<ref>{{cite web|title=Vice-Admiral James Dacres|url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p33594.htm#i335935|publisher=The Peerage.com}}</ref> \nOne son, also called James Richard Dacres, died at [[Mozambique]] at the age of 37 on 14 February 1848, while in command of the sloop {{HMS|Nimrod|1828|6}}. Another, Hew Dalrymple Dacres died at sea at the age of 21 on 11 July 1835, having been a lieutenant in the [[67th (South Hampshire) Regiment of Foot|67th Regiment]]. They and their father are commemorated in a plaque in the parish church at [[Tetbury]], [[Gloucestershire]].<ref name=\"Monument\">{{cite web|url=http://www.glosgen.co.uk/tetburymi.htm |title=Inscriptions on the Monuments existing in the Parish Church at Tetbury, Gloucestershire in 1857. |accessdate=30 January 2009 |work=Transcribed from \"The History of the Town and Parish of Tetbury\", by Rev. Alfred T. Lee, published in 1857. |publisher=Stuart Flight |year=2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090127053530/http://www.glosgen.co.uk/tetburymi.htm |archivedate=27 January 2009 }}</ref> One daughter, also called Arabella, married Colonel Thomas Butler of Hambledon, Hampshire. James Richard Dacres died at Catisfield Lodge, near [[Fareham]], [[Hampshire]] on 4 December 1853 at the age of 65.<ref name=\"GM202\"/> He was buried in the family vault at Tetbury.<ref name=\"GM202\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* {{cite wikisource |first=William Richard |last=O'Byrne |chapter=Dacres, James Richard (a) |title=A Naval Biographical Dictionary |year=1849 |publisher=[[John Murray (publisher)|John Murray]]}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n{{Refbegin}}\n*{{Colledge}}\n*{{Cite book |first=Nicholas|last=Tracy|title=Who's who in Nelson's Navy: 200 Naval Heroes|year=2006|publisher=Chatham Publishing|location=London|isbn=1-86176-244-5}}\n*{{Cite book |title=[[The Gentleman's Magazine]]|year=1837|location=London|publisher=F. Jefferies|volume=6}}\n*{{Cite book |title=The Gentleman's Magazine|year=1854|location=London|publisher=F. Jefferies|volume=196}}\n*{{Cite book |first=James|last=Dodsley|title=[[Annual Register]]|year=1854|location=London|publisher=F. J. Rivington|volume=95}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Borneman|first=Walter R.|authorlink=Walter R. Borneman|title=1812: The War That Forged a Nation|location=New York|publisher=Harper Perennial|year=2004|isbn=9780060531126|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/1812warthatforge0000born}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Forester|first=C.S.|authorlink=C. S. Forester|title=The Age of Fighting Sail|publisher=New English Library|isbn=0-939218-06-2}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-mil}}\n{{s-bef | before=[[Josceline Percy (Royal Navy officer)|Josceline Percy]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[Cape of Good Hope Station|Commander-in-Chief, Cape of Good Hope Station]] | years=1846}}\n{{s-aft | after=[[Barrington Reynolds]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dacres, James Richard}}\n[[Category:1788 births]]\n[[Category:1853 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Lowestoft]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy admirals]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy officers who were court-martialled]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy personnel of the French Revolutionary Wars]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy personnel of the Napoleonic Wars]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy personnel of the War of 1812]]\n[[Category:War of 1812 prisoners of war held by the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}{{Infobox military person\n|name=James Richard Dacres\n|birth_date=22 August 1788\n|death_date={{death date and age|df=yes|1853|12|4|1788|6|22}}\n|image=\n|caption=\n|birth_place = [[Lowestoft]]\n|death_place = Catisfield Lodge, near [[Fareham]], [[Hampshire]]\n|nickname=\n|residence =  [[United Kingdom]]\n|nationality =  [[United Kingdom|British]]\n|allegiance={{Flagcountry|UKGBI}}\n|serviceyears= 1796 &ndash; 1853\n|rank=[[Admiral (United Kingdom)|Vice-Admiral]]\n|branch= {{Navy|UK}}\n|commands={{HMS|Elk|1804|6}}<br>[[French corvette Bacchante (1795)|HMS ''Bacchante'']]<br>{{HMS|Guerriere|1806|6}}<br>{{HMS|Tiber|1813|6}}<br>{{HMS|Edinburgh|1811|6}}<br>[[Cape of Good Hope Station]]\n|unit=\n|battles=[[USS Constitution vs HMS Guerriere|USS ''Constitution'' vs HMS ''Guerriere'']]\n|awards=\n|relations=[[James Richard Dacres (1749\u20131810)|James Richard Dacres]] (father)<br>[[Barrington Dacres]] (brother)<br>[[Richard Dacres (Royal Navy officer)|Richard Dacres]] (uncle)<br>[[Sydney Dacres]] (cousin)\n}}\n\n'''James Richard Dacres''' (22 August 1788 &ndash; 4 December 1853) was an officer of the [[Royal Navy]] who saw service during the [[French Revolutionary War|French Revolutionary]] and [[Napoleonic Wars]], and the [[War of 1812]].  A member of a substantial naval dynasty, he eventually rose to the rank of [[Vice admiral (Royal Navy)|vice admiral]], but is chiefly remembered for his engagement with the American [[frigate]] {{USS|Constitution}} which saw the loss of his ship, {{HMS|Guerriere|1806|6}}.\n\n==Family and early life==\nDacres was born in [[Lowestoft]] on 22 August 1788, the son of Captain, later Vice-Admiral, [[James Richard Dacres (1749\u20131810)|James Richard Dacres]] and his wife Eleanor Blandford Pearce.<ref name=\"Whos Who108\">{{cite book |last=Tracy  |title=Who's who in Nelson's Navy |page=108}}</ref><ref name=\"GM201\">{{cite journal |title=Obituary: Vice-Admiral Dacres |journal=[[The Gentleman's Magazine]] |volume=XLI |issue=I |page=201 |url=http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=chi.79255342;view=1up;seq=213 |year=1854 |accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref> The Dacres would eventually become a substantial naval dynasty, James's elder brother [[Barrington Dacres]] embarked on a naval career and rose to be [[post-captain]], while their uncle, [[Richard Dacres (Royal Navy officer)|Richard Dacres]] became a vice-admiral. His cousin, Richard's son [[Sydney Dacres]] would eventually be an admiral, and [[First Sea Lord]].<ref name=\"Whos Who108\"/> James Richard Dacres entered the navy in 1796 at the age of eight, serving aboard his father's old ship, the 64-gun {{HMS|Sceptre|1781|6}}, as a first class volunteer.<ref name=\"GM201\"/> He moved aboard the 98-gun {{HMS|Barfleur|1768|6}} in 1797 and was present during the expedition to [[Ferrol, Spain|Ferrol]] in August 1800 as a lieutenant aboard the 74-gun [[French ship America (1788)|HMS ''Impetueux'']].<ref name=\"GM201\"/>\n\nHe was next reported aboard the 38-gun frigate {{HMS|Boadicea|1797|6}}, serving in the [[English Channel]] under Captain [[John Maitland (Royal Navy officer)|John Maitland]].<ref name=\"GM202\"/> On 24 July 1803 the French 74-gun [[third-rate]] [[HMS Implacable (1805)|''Duguay-Trouin'']] and the 38-gun frigate [[HMS Guerriere (1806)|''Guerri\u00e8re'']] were sighted sailing off [[Ferrol, Spain]].<ref name=\"Tracy238\">{{cite book |last=Tracy |title=Who's who in Nelson's Navy |page=238}}</ref><ref name=\"GM654\">{{cite book|title=Gentleman's Magazine|year=1837 |page=654}}</ref> Maitland decided to test whether the French ships were armed [[en fl\u00fbte]] and were being used as [[troopship]]s, and closing to within range, opened fire. The French returned fire, revealing they were fully armed and manned, and Maitland broke off. The French pursued, but were unable to catch him.<ref name=\"Tracy238\"/><ref name=\"GM654\"/> This marked Dacres's first encounter with the ''Guerri\u00e8re'', a ship he was later to command under the British flag.\n\nDacres then moved to the [[West Indies]], where his father was commander in chief of the [[Jamaica Station (Royal Navy)|Jamaica Station]]. He served for some time as [[flag lieutenant]] aboard {{HMS|Theseus|1786|6}} and [[French ship Hercule (1798)|HMS ''Hercule'']] before being appointed to his first command, that of the 18-gun [[Cruizer class brig-sloop|''Cruizer'' class]] [[brig-sloop]] {{HMS|Elk|1804|6}}.<ref name=\"GM202\">{{cite journal |title=Obituary: Vice-Admiral Dacres |journal=[[The Gentleman's Magazine]] |volume=XLI |issue=I |page=202 |url=http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=chi.79255342;view=1up;seq=214 |year=1854 |accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"AR275\">{{cite book|last=Dodsley|title=Annual Register|page=275}}</ref>\n\n==Command==\nDacres remained in command aboard the ''Elk'' until being transferred to the 24-gun {{HMS|Bacchante|1803|6}} on 14 January 1806.<ref name=\"GM202\"/><ref name=\"AR275\"/> While in command of her he captured the 3-gun French [[schooner]] ''Dauphin'', crewed with 71 men, off [[St. Domingo]] on 14 February 1807.<ref name=\"GM202\"/><ref name=\"AR275\"/> He then fell in with Captain [[William Furlong Wise]] of [[Ann and Amelia (1781 ship)|''Mediator'']] and together they navigated the waters around [[Saman\u00e1 (town)|Samana]] and planned an attack on the fort there, which was a notorious haven for [[privateer]]s. The two ships mounted a four-hour-long carronade, before [[Raid on Saman\u00e1|storming the defenders]]. They captured the fort, suffering two killed and 16 wounded in the process.<ref name=\"GM202\"/><ref name=\"AR275\"/> Dacres returned to England after this, but on his arrival in December 1807 no command could be found for him and he went on half-pay.<ref name=\"GM202\"/>\n\n===North America and the ''Guerriere''===\nHe returned to active service again on 18 March 1811, when he was appointed to command the former French frigate {{HMS|Guerriere|1806|6}}, which had been captured by [[HMS Amfitrite (1804)|HMS ''Blanche'']] on 19 July 1806.<ref name=\"Colledge150\">{{cite book|last=Colledge|title=Ships of the Royal Navy|page=150}}</ref>  Dacres sailed to the North American station, and shortly after the outbreak of the [[War of 1812]] was despatched by Vice-Admiral [[Herbert Sawyer]] as part of a squadron under Captain [[Philip Broke]] to intercept an American  squadron under Commodore [[John Rodgers (naval officer, War of 1812)|John Rodgers]]. Broke's squadron consisted of the 64-gun [[ship of the line]] {{HMS|Africa|1781|6}} and the frigates ''[[HMS Shannon (1806)|Shannon]]'', ''[[HMS Aeolus (1801)|Aeolus]]'', {{HMS|Belvidera|1809|2}} and ''Guerriere''.<ref name=\"Borneman82\">{{cite book|last=Borneman|title=1812: The War That Forged a Nation|page=82}}</ref>\n\nDacres briefly became separated from Broke's squadron, and while returning to them on 17 August came across the {{USS|Constitution}}, under Captain [[Isaac Hull]]. He mistook the other nearby ships, which was Broke's squadron, for the American squadron under Rodgers, and so missed an opportunity to close on the ''Constitution''.<ref name=\"Forester38\">{{cite book|last=Forester|title=The Age of Fighting Sail|page=38}}</ref> A chase ensued between the British and American ships, but the ''Constitution'' was finally able to escape Broke's squadron. Dacres remained with Broke, joining him in August in escorting an inbound convoy to [[City of Halifax|Halifax]], after which Dacres and the ''Guerriere'' were detached to sail to Halifax and undergo a refit.<ref name=\"Forester45\">{{cite book|last=Forester|title=The Age of Fighting Sail|page=45}}</ref>\n\n===Battling the ''Constitution''===\n{{Main|USS Constitution vs HMS Guerriere}}\n[[File:USS Constitution vs Guerriere.jpg|thumb|right|Painting of combat between USS ''Constitution'' and HMS ''Guerriere'' by Michel Felice Corne]]\nOn the afternoon of 19 August the ''Guerriere'' made contact with the ''Constitution''. Dacres prepared to fight and the two ships closed and exchanged broadsides for some time. The range eventually decreased and after a brief close exchange the ''Guerriere''{{'}}s mizzenmast was shot away, allowing the ''Constitution'' to rake her several times, causing considerable damage, before the two ships became entangled. Shortly after this ''Guerriere'' lost both her main and foremasts, leaving her largely un-manoeuvrable.<ref name=\"Forester52\">{{cite book|last=Forester|title=The Age of Fighting Sail|page=52}}</ref> During the engagement Dacres had been wounded by a musket-ball in the back while on the starboard forecastle, but had refused to leave the deck.<ref name=\"GM202\"/> ''Constitution'' then drew away to repair some damage, while Dacres attempted to set a jury rig. The attempt failed, and on ''Constitution''{{'}}s returning, Dacres fired a shot in the opposite direction to the ''Constitution''.<ref name=\"Borneman86\">{{cite book|last=Borneman|title=1812: The War That Forged a Nation|page=86}}</ref> Sensing that this was an attempt to signal surrender, Hull ordered a boat to take a lieutenant over to the British ship. When the lieutenant walked onto the ''Guerriere'' and asked if ''Guerriere'' was prepared to surrender, Captain Dacres responded \"Well, Sir, I don't know. Our mizzen mast is gone, our fore and main masts are gone-I think on the whole you might say we have struck our flag.\"<ref name=\"Borneman87\">{{cite book|last=Borneman|title=1812: The War That Forged a Nation|page=87}}</ref>\n\nDacres was brought aboard the ''Constitution'' where he presented his sword to Hull. Hull refused to accept it, saying he could not accept the sword from a man who had fought so gallantly.<ref name=\"Borneman87\"/>   Hull did, however, take procession of Dacres' hat to settle a wager the two had made earlier over who's ship was better.  Hull also ordered that Dacres' mother's Bible be returned to him.<ref name=\"Borneman87\"/> The ''Guerriere'' was assessed but found to be unsalvageable, and was blown up.<ref name=\"Colledge150\"/>\n\n===Aftermath===\n{{Wikisource|Letter from Captain James R. Dacres, RN, to Vice Admiral Herbert Sawyer, RN}}\nDacres briefly became a [[prisoner of war]], but was [[prisoner exchange|exchanged]] and returned to Halifax, where he was tried by [[court martial]] for the loss of his ship, which was standard procedure in the Royal Navy for the loss of a ship at the time.<ref name=\"GM202\"/><ref name=\"AR275\"/> He put forward as his defence the facts that the ''Guerriere'' was originally French-built and therefore not as sturdy as British-built ships, and that the ''Guerriere'' was badly decayed and on her way to refit in Halifax at the time, and the fall of the mizzen mast which crippled the ''Guerriere'' early in the fight had been due as much to rot as battle damage.<ref name=\"Forester50-1\">{{cite book|last=Forester|title=The Age of Fighting Sail|pages=50\u20131}}</ref> There was no suggestion that Dacres and his men had not done their utmost, or that Dacres had been unwise to engage the ''Constitution''. He was therefore honourably acquitted of all blame for the loss.<ref name=\"GM202\"/><ref name=\"AR275\"/><ref name=\"Forester56-7\">{{cite book|last=Forester|title=The Age of Fighting Sail|pages=56\u20137}}</ref> He was awarded a gratuity from the Lloyd's Patriotic Fund in consideration of his wound.<ref name=\"GM202\"/><ref name=\"AR275\"/>\n\n==Promotion==\nDacres continued to serve in the navy after his acquittal, and was appointed to the new 38-gun frigate {{HMS|Tiber|1813|6}} on 23 July 1814.<ref name=\"GM202\"/> He commanded her on the [[Cork (city)|Cork]], [[Newfoundland and Labrador|Newfoundland]] and Channel stations until 18 September 1818. On 8 March 1815 he captured the ''Leo'', a 3-gun American privateer under Captain George Coggeshell.<ref name=\"GM202\"/> He was appointed to command the 74-gun [[third rate]] {{HMS|Edinburgh|1811|6}} on 28 October 1833 until 1837.<ref name=\"GM202\"/> He became a rear-admiral on 28 June 1838, and commander-in-chief of the [[Cape of Good Hope Station]] on 9 August 1845, which was his last active employment.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hiscocks|first1=Richard|title=Cape Commander-in-Chief 1795-1852|url=http://morethannelson.com/commander-chief-cape/|website=morethannelson.com|publisher=morethannelson.com|accessdate=19 November 2016}}</ref> A temporary [[fort]] built in 1846 at the mouth of the [[Great Fish River|Fish River]] in the [[Eastern Cape|Eastern Cape Province]] during the [[Xhosa Wars#Seventh war|Seventh Xhosa War]] was named Fort Dacres in his honour. The construction was carried out by [[sailor]]s of the British [[man-of-war]] [[HMS President (1829)|HMS ''President'']].<ref>\n{{cite encyclopedia|title=Fort Dacres|encyclopedia=Standard Encyclopaedia of Southern Africa|volume=4|pages=646|publisher=Nasionale Opvoedkundige Uitgewery Ltd, Cape Town|date=1971|isbn = 0625003209}}</ref>\n\nHe was promoted to vice-admiral on 20 March 1848.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=20840|page=1182|date=24 March 1848}}</ref>\n\n==Family and later life==\nDacres married Arabella-Boyd, sister of [[Sir Adolphus Dalrymple, 2nd Baronet|Sir Adolphus Dalrymple]], on 25 April 1810.<ref name=\"GM202\"/> She died on 11 April 1828, but the marriage produced two sons and five daughters.<ref>{{cite web|title=Vice-Admiral James Dacres|url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p33594.htm#i335935|publisher=The Peerage.com}}</ref> \nOne son, also called James Richard Dacres, died at [[Mozambique]] at the age of 37 on 14 February 1848, while in command of the sloop {{HMS|Nimrod|1828|6}}. Another, Hew Dalrymple Dacres died at sea at the age of 21 on 11 July 1835, having been a lieutenant in the [[67th (South Hampshire) Regiment of Foot|67th Regiment]]. They and their father are commemorated in a plaque in the parish church at [[Tetbury]], [[Gloucestershire]].<ref name=\"Monument\">{{cite web|url=http://www.glosgen.co.uk/tetburymi.htm |title=Inscriptions on the Monuments existing in the Parish Church at Tetbury, Gloucestershire in 1857. |accessdate=30 January 2009 |work=Transcribed from \"The History of the Town and Parish of Tetbury\", by Rev. Alfred T. Lee, published in 1857. |publisher=Stuart Flight |year=2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090127053530/http://www.glosgen.co.uk/tetburymi.htm |archivedate=27 January 2009 }}</ref> One daughter, also called Arabella, married Colonel Thomas Butler of Hambledon, Hampshire. James Richard Dacres died at Catisfield Lodge, near [[Fareham]], [[Hampshire]] on 4 December 1853 at the age of 65.<ref name=\"GM202\"/> He was buried in the family vault at Tetbury.<ref name=\"GM202\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* {{cite wikisource |first=William Richard |last=O'Byrne |chapter=Dacres, James Richard (a) |title=A Naval Biographical Dictionary |year=1849 |publisher=[[John Murray (publisher)|John Murray]]}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n{{Refbegin}}\n*{{Colledge}}\n*{{Cite book |first=Nicholas|last=Tracy|title=Who's who in Nelson's Navy: 200 Naval Heroes|year=2006|publisher=Chatham Publishing|location=London|isbn=1-86176-244-5}}\n*{{Cite book |title=[[The Gentleman's Magazine]]|year=1837|location=London|publisher=F. Jefferies|volume=6}}\n*{{Cite book |title=The Gentleman's Magazine|year=1854|location=London|publisher=F. Jefferies|volume=196}}\n*{{Cite book |first=James|last=Dodsley|title=[[Annual Register]]|year=1854|location=London|publisher=F. J. Rivington|volume=95}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Borneman|first=Walter R.|authorlink=Walter R. Borneman|title=1812: The War That Forged a Nation|location=New York|publisher=Harper Perennial|year=2004|isbn=9780060531126|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/1812warthatforge0000born}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Forester|first=C.S.|authorlink=C. S. Forester|title=The Age of Fighting Sail|publisher=New English Library|isbn=0-939218-06-2}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-mil}}\n{{s-bef | before=[[Josceline Percy (Royal Navy officer)|Josceline Percy]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[Cape of Good Hope Station|Commander-in-Chief, Cape of Good Hope Station]] | years=1846}}\n{{s-aft | after=[[Barrington Reynolds]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dacres, James Richard}}\n[[Category:1788 births]]\n[[Category:1853 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Lowestoft]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy admirals]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy officers who were court-martialled]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy personnel of the French Revolutionary Wars]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy personnel of the Napoleonic Wars]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy personnel of the War of 1812]]\n[[Category:War of 1812 prisoners of war held by the United States]]\n", "name_user": "PhilHudson82", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBattling the Constitution:fixed typo: \"procession\" to \"possession\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Richard_Dacres_(Royal_Navy_officer,_born_1788)"}
{"title_page": "Senri Oe", "text_new": "{{short description|Japanese musician}}\n{{Copy edit|for=formatting and paragraph construction|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Senri Oe (musician)\n| native_name        = \u5927\u6c5f\u5343\u91cc\n| birth_date         = 6 September 1960 (age 59)\n| birth_place        = Fujiidera city, Osaka Japan\n| residence          = Brooklyn, New York\n| education          = Kwansei Gakuin University \nThe New School of Jazz\n| occupation         = Jazz pianist, composer, lyricist (Japanese), writer (Japanese)\n| years_active       = 1983 - present\n| website            = [http://www.peaceneverdie.com www.peaceneverdie.com]\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background       = solo_singer\n| instrument       = Piano, keyboard \n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n*[[Jazz]]\n*[[Pop music|pop]]\n*[[Rock music|rock]]\n*[[world music]]}}\n| label            = {{flatlist|\n*[[Sony Masterworks]]\n*[[Sony music direct]]\n*[http://www.peaceneverdie.com PND Records]}}\n| associated_acts  = {{flatlist|\n*[[Sheila Jordan]]\n*[[Jon Hendricks]]\n*[[Theo Bleckmann]]\n*[[Ari Hoenig]]\n*[[Matt Clohesy]]\n*[[Lawren Kinham]]}}\n}}\n}}\n\n{{Nihongo|'''Senri Oe'''|\u5927\u6c5f \u5343\u91cc|\u014ce Senri|born 6 September 1960}} is a Japanese jazz pianist, composer, producer, actor, singer, and songwriter. He is best known for his pop-music career in the 1980s and '90's-era Japanese pop music'. Among his releases (totalling 45 [[#Singles|singles]] and 18 original [[#Original albums (studio-recorded)|albums]]), from the 1980s to the 1990s, are eight albums which received [[Japan Gold Disc Award|Japan's Gold Disc Award]] (Japan's equivalent to a Grammy for Best Album). Senri Oe's other awards include the Gold Disc Award for Best Male Pop Artist in 1989.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wclk.com/post/april-30-japanese-pianist-senri-oe-performs-atlanta-jazz-festival-40-days-jazz-video|title=April 30: Japanese Pianist Senri Oe Performs For Atlanta Jazz Festival 40 Days Of Jazz (VIDEO)|last=Morris-Guity|first=JaJuan M.|website=www.wclk.com|language=en|access-date=2019-10-31}}</ref>\n\nSenri Oe's pop music garnered mass popularity in Japan following his first single \"Wallabee Shoes\" in 1983. He has held concerts in Japan's largest stadiums, including [[Nippon Budokan]], [[Yokohama Arena]], [[Yokohama Stadium]], [[Zozo Marine Stadium|Chiba Marine Stadium]], [[MetLife Dome|Seibu Dome]], [[NHK Hall]], and [[Osaka-j\u014d Hall|Osaka Castle Hall]].\n\nOe has also written and produced music for many artists, including [[Seiko Matsuda]], [[Misato Watanabe]], [[Hiromi Go]], [[Hikaru Genji (band)|Hikaru Genji]] and [[Sayuri Ishikawa]].\n\nHe has composed music for the soundtrack of the film ''[[Doraemon: Nobita's Great Adventure in the South Seas]]'', as well as \"Believe\" which was featured in [[Sanrio Puroland]].\n\n== Early life ==\nSenri Oe was born on September 6, 1960, in Fujiidera city [[Osaka]], [[Japan]]. Oe began playing piano at the age of three, and was classically trained by his junior high school teacher Yumi Nara, who would go on to become an acclaimed opera singer. After each of their lessons, Nara would encourage Oe to improvise, and eventually Oe began to compose.\n\nUpon being introduced to music by The Carpenters, Captain & Tenille and Gilbert O'Sullivan, Oe decided to become a singer-songwriter. Soon after, Oe's music repertoire expanded to include jazz musicians such as Chris Conor, Bill Evans, Thelonius Monk, Antonio Carlos Jobim, Winton Kelly, Miles Davis and Charlie Parker.\n\nIn 1975, Oe participated in the final [[Yamaha Popular Song Contest]] POPCON (akin to American Idol).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://chicagomusicguide.com/featured-artist-senri-oe/|title=FEATURED ARTIST - Senri Oe|date=2018-06-24|website=Chicago Music Guide|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-31}}</ref>\n\nIn 1980, Oe entered [[Kwansei Gakuin University]] and majored in economics while simultaneously beginning to pursue a professional music career. He formed his first bands during his time at university, was scouted by [[Sony Music Entertainment Japan|Sony Music]] and signed to [[Epic Records Japan|Epic Sony]] Japan in 1981.\n\n== Music career ==\n\n=== 1983-1984: Early pop career and debut album ===\nOn February 27, 1983, Oe performed on [[Sapporo Television Broadcasting|STV Radio]]'s Sunday Jumbo Special in Sapporo, Hokkaido, granting him his initial exposure as a professional musician. Within this segment, Oe began a ten-minute performance in which he improvised a song on live radio.\n\nOe soon released his first single \"Wallabee Shoes  (\u30ef\u30e9\u30d3\u30fc\u306c\u304e\u3059\u3066\u3066),\" followed by his debut album, WAKUWAKU. Quickly garnering popularity, \"Wallabee Shoes\" charted at No. 10 in Sapporo radio.\n\nOe appeared on [[All Night Fuji]] (Akin to Saturday Night Live in Japan) on Channel 8 alongside [[Epic Records Japan|Epic Sony]] label-mates [[Wham!|Wham]] from Britain.\n\n=== 1985-2007: Greater pop music career success ===\nDirectly after graduating from [[Kwansei Gakuin University]], Oe rose to fame in November 1984 with the success of his sixth single, \"10 People, 10 Colors (\u5341\u4eba\u5341\u8272).\" His third album, Miseinen (\u672a\u6210\u5e74) Juvenile charted at No. 5 on [[Oricon]] (Japanese equivalent to the Billboard weekly chart).\n\nWith his now growing popularity across Japan, Oe toured performing in Japan's largest venues and stadiums, including [[Nippon Budokan]] (with [[seating capacity]] of 14,471, akin to Madison Square Garden) to promote his fifth album, AVEC Tour Final, in 1987.\n\nOe's seventh album 1234 was awarded Album of the Year in the third [[Japan Gold Disc Award|Gold Disc Awards]] (Japan's equivalent of the Grammy Awards) in the Pop Male Solo Artist Category.\n\nContinuing to tour large venues throughout Japan, Oe released the album, ''Sloppy Joe'', on March 25, 1989, which charted at No. 2 on the [[Oricon]] (Japan's equivalent of Billboard weekly chart).\n\nMeanwhile, Oe appeared as an actor on television for the first time, in the dramatic show entitled Kimi Ga Uso Wo Tuita.\n\nOe's ninth album, APOLLO, was the first of his albums to be recorded in New York City. The album was released to critical acclaim, charting at No.1 in the [[Oricon]] weekly chart on September, 21st 1990. Following APOLLO's success, Oe again toured in stadiums ([[Yokohama Stadium]], [[MetLife Dome|Seibu Dome]], [[Zozo Marine Stadium|Chiba Marine Stadium]], [[Yokohama Arena]], [[Osaka-j\u014d Hall|Osaka Castle Hall]]).\n\nOe's single \"Never See You Again (\u683c\u597d\u60aa\u3044\u3075\u3089\u308c\u304b\u305f) Kakko Warui Furare Kata\" was released in September 1990 and was his highest-charting single to date, charting at No.2 in the Oricon weekly chart.\n\nWhile continuing to record and perform, in 2000 Oe established his own record label, Station Kids Records, an imprint of Sony Music Entertainment Japan.\n\nOe also began to branch out to musical composition beyond pop music. Among these projects, he scored the soundtrack for the film Noto No Hanayome,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm1217486/|title=Senri Oe|website=IMDb|access-date=2019-10-31}}</ref> [[Sanrio Puroland]] Park's Musical titled Believe, music for the performances of illusionist [[Princess Tenko]] Play, for Destiny. Also, notably, Oe scored music for the Japanese animated film ''[[Doraemon: Nobita's Great Adventure in the South Seas]]'', as well as \"Kono Hoshino Dokokade\" by Yasuda Sisters.\n\n=== 2008-2012: Career shift to jazz ===\nOn December 22, 2007, Oe announced that he would study jazz music in [[School of Jazz (The New School)|The New School for Jazz]] and moved to Manhattan on January 10, 2008, with his then puppy, a [[dachshund]] named Peace.\n\nSince Oe was fifteen years old, he was intent on learning jazz music theory at school. Due to his pop singer-songwriter career unexpectedly taking off, he chose to pause his jazz aspirations later in life.\n\n=== 2012-Present: Beginning of jazz pianist career ===\nAfter graduating from The New School for Jazz, Oe launched his jazz record label in 2012. It was called \"Peace Never Die\" Records, abbreviated to PND Records. His dog, Peace, also appeared in PND's logo. Peace has received a certificate which allows her to officially qualify as an emotional support dog for Oe.\n\nOe's jazz debut album was ''Boys Mature Slow''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jazzmusicarchives.com/video/senri-oe/5600|title=SENRI OE Boys mature slow /Senri Oe (video)|website=JazzMusicArchives.com|language=en|access-date=2019-10-31}}</ref>\n\nFollowing conversations with former Tokyo Jazz Festival producer, Atsuko Yashima, Oe concluded that his second album's style could expand to include for a jazz 'big band' ensemble.\n\nOe composed eleven pieces for his next album, ''Spooky Hotel'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kennedy-center.org/artist/B214393|title=Senri Oe|website=www.kennedy-center.org|access-date=2019-10-31}}</ref> which was released in 2013.\n\nFollowing ''Spooky Hotel'', Oe's big band performed in the Tokyo Jazz Festival at Tokyo Forum A Hall.\n\nOe  worked towards composing for a drum-less trio was entitled Collective Scribble;<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bluenote.co.jp/jp/reports/2015/05/05/senri-oe-ny-trio-collective-scribble-tour-2015.html|title=Senri Oe Trio Bluenote collective Scribble|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Oe remarked that here, saxophone and piano combined with upright bass, \"like a drawing scribble.\"\n\nAt the same time, Oe was creating his fourth jazz vocal album, ''Answer July'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jazzspeaks.org/senri-oe-record-release-answer-july/|title=Senri Oe Record Release: Answer July|website=Jazz Speaks|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://musicalmemoirs.wordpress.com/2016/07/15/new-cd-releases-reflect-sounds-of-summer-and-celebrate-men-of-jazz/|title=NEW CD RELEASES REFLECT SOUNDS OF SUMMER and CELEBRATE MEN OF JAZZ|date=2016-07-15|website=Musicalmemoirs's Blog|language=en|access-date=2019-10-31}}</ref> with [[Sheila Jordan]], [[Jon Hendricks]], [[Theo Bleckmann]] and [https://laurenkinhan.com/about/ Lauren Kinhan].\n\n''Answer July'' was a Grammy-nominated consideration album in the Best Jazz Album in 2017.\n\nIn addition, Oe challenged himself to adopt the concept of combining pop with jazz in his fifth studio jazz album ''Boys & Girls'',<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.axs.com/interview-j-pop-star-turned-jazz-man-senri-oe-talks-solo-piano-for-det-132772|title=Interview: J-Pop star-turned-jazz man Senri Oe talks solo piano for Detroit Jazz Fest|work=AXS|access-date=2019-10-31|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.detroitnews.com/story/entertainment/music/2018/04/11/detroit-jazz-festival-chick-corea-bassist-esparanza-spaulding-drummer-terri-lyne-carrington/33738717/|title=2018 Detroit Jazz Fest lineup boasts diversity|website=Detroit News|language=en|access-date=2019-10-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khon2.com/living-808/japanese-superstar-senri-oe-plays-the-blue-note/|title=Japanese Superstar Senri Oe plays the Blue Note|date=2019-05-21|website=KHON2|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fox2detroit.com/mornings/jazz-pianist-senri-oe-performs|title=Jazz pianist Senri Oe performs|date=2018-09-03|website=FOX 2 Detroit|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jazziz.com/a-whole-new-world-senri-oe-gets-his-kicks-as-a-jazz-pianist/|title=A Whole New World: Senri Oe Gets His Kicks As a Jazz Pianist|last=Magazine|first=JAZZIZ|date=2018-12-15|website=JAZZIZ Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-31}}</ref> released in 2018. On ''Boys & Girls'', Oe selected some of his most popular pop songs to reinterpret into jazz compositions (which Oe calls, \"Senri Jazz\"). ''Boys & Girls'' charted at No. 1 in Japan Billboard's \"Jazz and Classical Music Chart\". Following this release, Oe toured to promote the new album in Amsterdam, Mexico City, and throughout the United States.\n\nRecently, Oe released his sixth studio jazz album ''Hmmm''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.northcoastvoice.com/PDFs/v19i10.pdf|title=North Coast Voice|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehollywoodtimes.today/jazz-pianist-senri-oe-sixth-album-release-hmmm-out-now-and-interview/|title=Jazz Pianist Senri Oe Sixth Album Release 'HMMM' Out Now & Interview {{!}} The Hollywood Times|last=thehollywoodtimes|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://debbieburkeauthor.com/2019/09/14/j-pop-star-senri-oe-makes-death-defying-hairpin-turn-into-jazz/|title=J-pop Star Senri Oe Makes Death-Defying Hairpin Turn into Jazz|date=2019-09-14|website=Debbie Burke|language=en|access-date=2019-10-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jazzweekly.com/2019/09/senri-oe-hmmm/|title=Senri Oe Hmmm|last=|first=|date=|website=www.jazzweekly.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-31}}</ref> in 2019. Both the recordings and performances have featured bandmates [[Ari Hoenig]] (drums) and Matt Clohesy (upright bass).\n\n== Discography ==\n\n=== Singles ===\n\n==== Pop ====\n\n* Wallabee Shoes \u30ef\u30e9\u30d3\u30fc\u306c\u304e\u3059\u3066\u3066 (1983)\n* Girl Friend (1983)\n* Futatsu no Shukudai (1983)\n* Boys & Girls (1984)\n* Romance (1984)\n* 10 People, 10 Colors \u5341\u4eba\u5341\u8272 (1984)\n* Real (1985)\n* Friend (1985)\n* Cosmopolitan (1986)\n* Kimi to Ikitai (1986)\n* Bedtime Stories, Man on the Earth (1986)\n* YOU (1987)\n* Power (1987)\n* Glory Days (1988)\n* Korekara (1988)\n* Onegai Tengoku (1989)\n* Radio ga yonderu (1989)\n* We are Traveling Band (1989)\n* Tawawa no Kajitsu (1999)\n* dear (1990)\n* APOLLO (1990)\n* Aitai (1990)\n* Never See You Again \u683c\u597d\u60aa\u3044\u3075\u3089\u308c\u304b\u305f (1991)\n* HONEST (1992)\n* Arigato (1992)\n* Gunbai wa Docchi ni Agaru (1991)\n* Yuki no Wakare (1993)\n* Kimi wo motome tsuzukeru kagiri (1991)\n* Natsu no kesshin (1994)\n* Shiroi Yuki Maiorita (1994)\n* Nando mo sakenda (1995)\n* Sayonara mo iezuni (1996)\n* Hyperactive Dinosaur (1997)\n* Two of us (1998)\n* New Public! / Akiuta (1998)\n* Yakyu no Natsu (1999)\n* Billboard (2000)\n* Kiseki (2001)\n* This Christmas (2001)\n* Oyasumi (2002)\n* Let it be, SWEET (2002)\n* Equal (2002)\n* Seijyaku no basho (2007)\n\n=== Original albums (studio recorded) ===\n\n==== Pop era ====\n\n* WAKU WAKU (1983)\n* Pleasure (1984)\n* Miseinen (1985)\n* Chibusa (1985)\n* AVEC (1986)\n* OLYMPIC (1987)\n* 1234 (1988)\n* Redmonky Yellowfish (1989)\n* Apollo (1990)\n* HOMME (1991)\n* Rokko Oroshifuita (1992)\n* Giant Steps (1994)\n* SENRI HAPPY (1996)\n* ROOM (1998)\n* Solitude (2000)\n* First Class (2001)\n* Untitled Love Songs (2002)\n* Ghostwriter (2005)\n\n==== Jazz era ====\n\n* Boys Mature Slow (2012)\n* Spooky Hotel (2013)\n* Collective Scribble (2015)\n* Answer July (2016)\n* Boys & Girls (2018)\n* Hmmm (2019)\n\n=== Best Albums ===\n\n* Sloppy Joe (1989)\n* Sloppy Joe II (1994)\n* WINTER JOE (1998)\n* 2000 JOE (1999)\n* THE LEGEND (2003)\n* Sloppy Joe III (2006)\n* Golden Best Senri Oe (2011)\n* Sloppy Joe I & II (2013)\n\n=== Self covered album ===\n\n* Home at last ~ Senri Sings Senri ~\n\n=== Live album ===\n\n* Live \"Ghost Note\" at Motion Blue YOKOHAMA (2006)\n\n=== Instrumental albums ===\n* 12 kagetsu (2003)\n* ghost note (2005)\n\n=== Others ===\n1. Untokodokkoisho (2007)\n\n2. Duo (2010)\n\n=== CD-Box ===\n\n* Senri Premium ~MY GLORY DAYS 1983 - 1988 (2008)\n\n=== Soundtracks ===\n\n* Doraemon: Nobita's Great Adventure in the South Sea (1998)\n* Doraemon: Nobita's Drift in the Universe (1999)\n* Two Tables (2002)\n* Noto no Hanayome (2008)\n\n== Videography ==\n\n=== Music videos =